        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-03-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-03-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="287" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d287">
                <head>No. 287.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">West</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-03-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 10, 1883</date>.
                                (Received March 13.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your note of the 18th of
                            January last, I have the honor to inform you that Earl Granville has
                            requested me to communicate to you the substance of a dispatch received
                            from Her Majesty’s minister at Caracas, which is to the following
                            effect: Mr. Baker, the United States representative, has informed Her
                            Majesty’s minister that he will submit to him the proposals which he
                            contemplates making to the Venezuelan Government with regard to the
                            custody of ships’ papers; and should they appear to meet the
                            circumstances of the case, Her Majesty’s minister, in compliance with
                            his instructions, will support Mr. Baker in a note to be addressed to
                            the Venezuelan Government.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>L. S. SACKVILLE WEST.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
